  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Number of Islands\n\nCount groups of land cells connected horizontally or vertically in a grid of `1` and `0` characters.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: grid = [[1,1,0],[0,1,0],[1,0,1]]\nOutput: 3\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: grid = [[1,1],[1,1]]\nOutput: 1\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: grid = [[0,0],[0,0]]\nOutput: 0\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Inputs are sized for local offline execution.\n- Return values follow the method description.",
  "editorial": "Use the graph structure directly: traverse reachable states, maintain visited or distance state, and update the answer when each node or cell is settled.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def numIslands(self, grid):\n        rows, cols = len(grid), len(grid[0])\n        def dfs(r, c):\n            if r < 0 or c < 0 or r == rows or c == cols or grid[r][c] != '1':\n                return\n            grid[r][c] = '0'\n            dfs(r + 1, c); dfs(r - 1, c); dfs(r, c + 1); dfs(r, c - 1)\n        count = 0\n        for r in range(rows):\n            for c in range(cols):\n                if grid[r][c] == '1':\n                    count += 1\n                    dfs(r, c)\n        return count\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Model the state explicitly.",
    "Prefer linear or near-linear graph traversal when possible."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def numIslands(self, grid):\n        pass\n"
  },
